ld English <i>Spyrling</i>. It has been suggested that this could be a metathesized and shortened form of Old English <i>Sprytling</i>, a derivative of <i>Spryt(t)el</i>, which forms the first element in the Lincolnshire placename <i>Spridlington</i>, though the etymology of the placename is uncertain.","English: from Middle English <i>sperling</i>, <i>sparling</i>, <i>spirling</i>, <i>spurling</i>, Anglo-Norman French <i>esperlinge</i>, Middle Dutch <i>spierlinc</i>, denoting some kind of small fish, perhaps smelt, sprat, pilchard, or whiting. It may have been given to someone who caught, sold, or resembled such fish.","Americanized form of German   Sperling  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Spurling","meanings":["English: variant of   Sparling  ."]},{"name":"Sperling","meanings":["German: nickname from a diminutive of Middle High German <i>spar(e)</i> ‘sparrow’.","Jewish (Ashkenazic): artificial name from German <i>Sperling</i> ‘sparrow’.","English (Middlesex): variant of   Sparling  ."]}]},{"name":"Lydia","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Of Greek origin, meaning ‘woman from Lydia’, an area of Asia Minor. The name is borne in the Bible by a woman of Thyatira who was converted by St Paul and who entertained him in her house (Acts 16:14–15, 40). It has enjoyed steady popularity in the English-speaking world since the 17th century."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Lydia Sparling was born in 1280, in Argyll, Scotland as the daughter of George Sparling. She married John House in 1298. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. She died in Argyll and Bute, Scotland, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1280–":"1280–Surnud","1280–Female":"1280–Surnud","1280–1313":"1280–1313","1299–Male":"1299–Surnud","1302–1338":"1302–1338","1250–1310":"1250–1310","1338":"1338","1302":"1302","1313":"1313","2 September 1302":"2. september 1302","ABT 1299":"umbes 1299","1310":"1310","1299":"1299","1298":"1298